user..name@example.com` with MailAddress, and uses Uri for 10K+ character URLs.\nWhat breaks?","attachments":[],"interactionId":"8b03f073-01d3-4390-bdd1-f483a12cfdf9"},"id":"4650853d-666a-40af-9be0-4bd9a745cce5","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:44:08.347Z","parentId":"35ce75d3-760b-45f6-96a2-2d741bb7761c"}
{"type":"hook.start","data":{"hookInvocationId":"d59b7352-785b-42be-872c-28bc716ef6e7","hookType":"sessionStart","input":{"sessionId":"b1c360cd-a4ad-4b6c-b145-0dc53d8c287e","timestamp":1775612648348,"cwd":"/tmp/sv-26a6f7f1f8f047a7b0f5d5f40cd1ac3d","source":"new","initialPrompt":"I'm migrating a .NET 9 app to .NET 10. Here's code that worked before:\n\n```csharp\n[JsonPolymorphic(TypeDiscriminatorPropertyName = \"Type\")]\n[JsonDerivedType(typeof(Dog), \"dog\")]\npublic abstract class Animal\n{\n    public abstract string Type { get; }\n}\n\npublic class Dog : Animal\n{\n    public override string Type => \"Dog\";\n}\n\n// This produced {\"Type\":\"dog\",\"Type\":\"Dog\"} in .NET 9 — broken JSON but it serialized\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize<Animal>(new Dog());\n```\n\n```csharp\npublic class OrderDto\n{\n    public int Id { get; set; }\n    [Obsolete(\"Use ShippingAddress instead\")]\n    public string Address { get; set; }\n    public string ShippingAddress { get; set; }\n}\nvar xml = new XmlSerializer(typeof(OrderDto));\n// In .NET 9, Address was not included in the serialized output\n```\n\nThe app also validates email addresses like `user..name@example.com` with MailAddress, and uses Uri for 10K+ character URLs.\nWhat breaks?\n"}},"id":"c0b536e8-cd52-4645-b54b-d16bb2adc1ef","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:44:08.348Z","parentId":"4650853d-666a-40af-9be0-4bd9a745cce5"}
